Data Synchronization Strategies: From Source Database to Elasticsearch 

 

Option 1: Direct Ingestion (Spring Boot → Elasticsearch) 

Overview 

In this approach, our Spring Boot application acts as the direct bridge. It is responsible for three steps: 

Pulling data from our database. 

Translating that data into a format Elasticsearch understands. 

Pushing it directly to the Elasticsearch cluster using the modern Java Client. 

Think of this as "direct delivery"—there is no middleman. Our application manages the entire journey of the data. 

 

How We Will Make It Efficient 

The "Box" Method (Bulk Processing): Instead of sending every single database row one by one (which is very slow), we will group them into "boxes" of 1,000 records. We send one large request instead of 1,000 small ones. This drastically reduces the load on our network and Elasticsearch. 

Smart Scaling (Work Sharing): If we run multiple instances of our application, we need to make sure they don't work on the same data. We will use a "Status" column in our database (e.g., is_indexed). 

The "Skip Locked" Trick: We will use a database feature called SKIP LOCKED. This allows Instance A to grab the first 1,000 rows while Instance B automatically skips those and grabs the next 1,000. This lets us scale horizontally without any data overlapping. 

 

Pros (The Benefits) 

Simple Architecture: We don’t need to install or manage extra software like Kafka or Logstash. This keeps our infrastructure "lean." 

Total Control: Since the logic lives in our Java code, we have 100% control over how the data is transformed or cleaned before it reaches the search engine. 

Lower Costs: Fewer moving parts mean lower cloud hosting costs and less maintenance work for our DevOps team. 

Cons (The Risks) 

Direct Pressure: If Elasticsearch becomes slow, our application will also slow down because it is waiting for a response. 

No Safety Net: If both the application and Elasticsearch have issues at the same time, we have to be very careful to ensure no data "falls through the cracks" during the transfer. 

App Heavy-Lifting: The application has to spend CPU and Memory power on moving data, which could otherwise be used for user features. 

 

The Modern Implementation (Java Client) 

Avoid the deprecated RestHighLevelClient. Use the Elasticsearch Java Client (introduced in 7.17/8.x). 

Key Dependency: 

<dependency> 
   <groupId>co.elastic.clients</groupId> 
   <artifactId>elasticsearch-java</artifactId> 
