</dependency> 

 

 

Our Proposed Solutions for a Reliable Build 

Potential Failure 

What Happens? 

Our Solution 

Elasticsearch is Offline 

The app tries to send data but gets a "Connection Refused" error. 

Spring Retry: We will use a retry policy. The app will wait 5 seconds, then 10, then 30 to try again before giving up. 

The App Crashes During Push 

The app has pulled data from the DB but dies before Elasticsearch confirms receipt. 

Transactional Safety: We only change the status in the DB from PENDING to SUCCESS after we get a "thumbs up" from Elasticsearch. On restart, the app simply picks up the PENDING rows again. 

Data Format Error 

A specific record has a "text" value where Elasticsearch expects a "number," causing a crash. 

Dead Letter Logging: We will catch these specific errors, log the "Bad ID," and mark it as FAILED  so it doesn't block the rest of the queue. 

Elasticsearch is "Too Busy" 

Our app is sending data faster than Elasticsearch can write it (Backpressure). 

Circuit Breaker: We use a tool called Resilience4j. If it detects Elasticsearch is struggling, it "opens the circuit" and stops sending data for a few minutes to let the engine recover. 

Duplicate Data Creation 

A network glitch makes the app send the same data twice. 

ID Mapping: By forcing Elasticsearch to use our Database Primary Key as its internal ID, the second request will simply overwrite the first one instead of creating a duplicate. 

 

Step 1: Infrastructure Setup (The Connection) 

To begin, we need an Elasticsearch cluster (either hosted on-premise or in the cloud). 

Security: We will set up an API Key or a Username/Password in Elasticsearch for our Spring Boot app to use. 

The Index: We will pre-create the "Index" (the search table) in Elasticsearch and define its "Mapping" (telling it which fields are dates, numbers, or text). 

 

Step 2: Application Configuration 

We need to tell our Spring Boot app where Elasticsearch lives. We do this in the application.yml file and a small Java config class. 

