The Java Client Setup: 

code Java 

downloadcontent_copy 

expand_less 

@Configuration 
public class ElasticConfig { 
   @Bean 
   public ElasticsearchClient getClient() { 
       // We set up the "Phone Line" to talk to Elasticsearch here 
       RestClient restClient = RestClient.builder(new HttpHost("our-es-cluster", 9200)).build(); 
       ElasticsearchTransport transport = new RestClientTransport(restClient, new JacksonJsonpMapper()); 
       return new ElasticsearchClient(transport); 
   } 
} 

 

Step 3: The Data Extraction Logic  

We will create a service that periodically asks the database: "Which records have changed and are not yet in the search engine?" 

Efficiency: We use the SKIP LOCKED SQL command. This allows our app to grab a batch of 500 or 1,000 records safely, even if we have multiple instances of the app running. 

The Query: SELECT * FROM products WHERE needs_sync = true LIMIT 500 FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED. 

 

Step 4: The Ingestion Logic  

Once we have the 500 records, we don't send them one-by-one. We use the Bulk API. 

The Java Implementation: 

code Java: 

 

public void shipToElastic(List<Product> products) { 
   BulkRequest.Builder br = new BulkRequest.Builder(); 
 
   for (Product product : products) { 
       br.operations(op -> op 
           .index(idx -> idx 
               .index("products_search") 
               .id(product.getId().toString()) // Keeps data unique 
               .document(product) 
           ) 
       ); 
   } 
 
   // We send the whole batch at once 
   BulkResponse response = client.bulk(br.build()); 
 
   // If ES says "OK", we update our DB status to 'SUCCESS' 
   if (!response.errors()) { 
       updateDatabaseStatus(products, "SUCCESS"); 
   } else { 
       // We look for specific errors in the batch 
       handlePartialErrors(response); 
   } 
} 

 

Step 5: Failure Handling & "Self-Healing" 

Since we don't have a message broker (like Kafka) to act as a safety net, we build the safety directly into our code: 

The "Retry" Strategy: If the network flickers and the "Shipment" fails, we do not update the status. The app will simply try again in the next scheduled cycle (e.g., 5 minutes later). 

Circuit Breakers: We will use a library called Resilience4j. If Elasticsearch goes down completely, the "Circuit Breaker" will trip. This tells our app: "Stop trying to fetch from the DB for now; the search engine is sick. Let's wait 5 minutes before trying again." This prevents our app from wasting CPU power and crashing itself. 

Dead Letter Logging: If a specific record is "corrupt" (e.g., a field is too long), Elasticsearch will reject it. We will catch this specific error, log it for our developers to see, and mark that one row as FAILED in the database so it doesn't block the rest of the records. 

 

 

 

Option 2: Messaging Buffer (Spring Boot -> kafka/RabbitMQ -> Logstash -> ES) 

How it Works (The Concept) 

Instead of our Spring Boot app talking directly to Elasticsearch, it puts the data into a high-speed "Digital Post Office" (Kafka or RabbitMQ). A separate worker (Logstash) then picks up that mail and delivers it to Elasticsearch. 

This creates a decoupled system: the part of the app that reads the database doesn't need to care if the search engine is currently awake or busy. 

 

Our Implementation Steps 

The Producer (Spring Boot): We will configure our app to read from the database and "publish" those records as messages to a Kafka Topic. 

The Message Broker (Kafka): This acts as our massive waiting room. It stores our data safely on a disk until it is successfully processed. 

The Consumer (Logstash): We will set up Logstash to "listen" to Kafka. As soon as a new message arrives, Logstash pulls it, cleans it up if necessary, and pushes it to Elasticsearch. 

The Destination (Elasticsearch): Receives the clean data from Logstash and makes it searchable. 

 

Pros and Cons 

Pros (The Benefits): 

Ultimate Reliability: If Elasticsearch goes down for maintenance for 3 hours, no data is lost. Kafka simply holds onto it and waits. 

Traffic Control (Backpressure): If we suddenly have 1 million database updates, we won't crash Elasticsearch. Kafka buffers the load, and Logstash "sips" the data at a speed Elasticsearch can handle. 

Independent Scaling: If we have a huge backlog, we can simply start more "Logstash" instances to clear the queue faster without touching our main application. 

Cons (The Challenges): 

Infrastructure Overhead: We need to manage Kafka and Logstash, which requires more server resources and setup time. 

Slight Latency: Data might take an extra second or two to appear in search results because it has to travel through the "Post Office" first. 

 

Failure Scenarios & Our Solutions 

In this high-scale model, we handle failures by isolating them. 

Potential Failure 

What Happens? 

Our Solution 

Elasticsearch is Offline 

Logstash cannot deliver the data. 

Automatic Pausing: Logstash will stop pulling messages from Kafka and wait. The data remains 100% safe inside Kafka until Elasticsearch is back online. 

Logstash Crashes 

The "Delivery Truck" stops moving. 

Consumer Offsets: Kafka remembers exactly which message Logstash read last. When Logstash restarts, it picks up exactly where it left off—no missed data. 

Spring Boot Crashes 

The app stops sending data to Kafka. 

DB Checkpointing: Our app tracks the "Last Processed ID" in the database. Upon restart, it simply resumes from that ID. 

Kafka is Offline 

The app cannot "post" its messages. 

Local Retry: We will configure the Spring Boot Kafka Template to retry the connection and, if necessary, stop the DB extraction until the broker is healthy. 

Bad/Corrupt Data 

A record has an error that prevents it from being indexed. 

Dead Letter Queue (DLQ): Instead of the whole system getting "stuck" on a bad record, Logstash will move the "bad" message to a separate "Error Topic" for us to inspect later. 

 

Tools We Will Use to Implement This 

Spring Kafka: To allow our application to talk to the broker with minimal code. 

Apache Kafka: Our chosen message broker (it is the industry standard for high-speed data streaming). 

Logstash Kafka Input Plugin: A pre-built tool that connects Kafka to Elasticsearch without us having to write custom "Consumer" code. 

Kibana Monitoring: To watch our Kafka "lag" (how much data is waiting in the queue) so we know if we need to scale up. 

 

Here is how we will set this up and the steps we will take to build it. 

Step 1: Setting up the Infrastructure  

Before writing code, we need the "Post Office" (Kafka) and the "Delivery Truck" (Logstash) running. 

Kafka Setup: We will set up a Kafka cluster (at least 3 nodes for high availability). Inside Kafka, we create a Topic (a dedicated channel) called db-to-search-sync. 

Logstash Setup: We install Logstash on a server that has access to both Kafka and Elasticsearch. 

 

Step 2: Preparing the Database  

The Log Reader: We will use a CDC tool (like Debezium) that sits next to the database. Its only job is to watch that log and instantly turn every change into a message. 

Step 3: Building the Spring Boot Producer  

This is the code inside our application that moves data from the DB to Kafka. 

What we use: spring-kafka library. 

The Code Logic: 

Fetch: Use the SKIP LOCKED method (mentioned in Option 1) to grab 500 PENDING rows. 

Convert: Turn the database rows into JSON strings. 

Send: Use the KafkaTemplate to "publish" the JSON to our Kafka topic. 

Confirm: Once Kafka says "I have it," we update the DB status to IN_QUEUE. 

code : 

// Simplified logic example 
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 5000) // Runs every 5 seconds 
public void sendToKafka() { 
   List<ProductEntity> data = repository.findBatchToSend(); 
   for (ProductEntity product : data) { 
       kafkaTemplate.send("db-to-search-sync", product.getId().toString(), product.toJson()); 
       product.setSyncStatus("IN_QUEUE"); 
       repository.save(product); 
   } 
} 

 

Step 4: Configuring Logstash  

Logstash doesn't require us to write Java code. Instead, we write a Configuration File that tells it how to move data from Kafka to Elasticsearch. 

The Logstash Instruction Sheet (logstash.conf): 

code : 

input { 
 kafka { 
   bootstrap_servers => "kafka-broker:9092" 
   topics => ["db-to-search-sync"] 
   group_id => "logstash-consumer-group" # Remembers where it left off 
 } 
} 
 
filter { 
 # We can clean or transform data here if needed 
 json { source => "message" } 
} 
 
output { 
 elasticsearch { 
   hosts => ["http://elasticsearch:9200"] 
   index => "products_search" 
   document_id => "%{id}" # Matches DB ID to prevent duplicates 
 } 
} 

 

Step 5: Managing Failures & Safety Checks 

To ensure 99.9% reliability, we apply these specific configurations: 

Acks = All: We configure the Spring Boot app to wait for a "Full Receipt" from Kafka before moving to the next record. This ensures Kafka has safely written the data to its disk. 

Consumer Offsets: Logstash is configured to use "Consumer Groups." If Logstash is turned off for an hour, Kafka remembers exactly which message was the last one Logstash read. When it turns back on, it starts from that exact spot. 

Persistent Queues: We will enable Logstash's "Persistent Queue" feature. If Logstash receives a message but Elasticsearch is down, Logstash stores that message on its own local hard drive as a second layer of safety. 

Dead Letter Topic: If a message is "broken" (e.g., bad JSON), Kafka will move it to a sync-failed-debug topic so we can fix it without stopping the rest of the system. 

 

Option 3, which we call the "Log-and-Ship" strategy. In this model, we treat our data like a diary. Our application simply "writes it down" in a local file, and a specialized "courier" (Filebeat) handles the delivery to Elasticsearch. 

 

Option 3: Log-Based Shipping (The "Courier" Strategy) 

How it Works (The Concept) 

Instead of our Spring Boot app trying to manage network connections to Elasticsearch or Kafka, it simply writes the database records into a JSON log file on the server's hard drive. 

A tiny, high-speed agent called Filebeat, sits on the same server. It "watches" the log file. Every time a new line is written, Filebeat picks it up and ships it to Elasticsearch. 

 

Our Implementation Steps 

The Logger (Spring Boot): We will use a library called logstash-logback-encoder. We will create a dedicated "Search Logger" in our app that formats our database records into clean JSON lines. 

The Storage (Local Disk): The app writes these JSON lines to a specific folder (e.g., /var/logs/search-sync/*.json). 

The Courier (Filebeat): We install Filebeat on the server. We tell it: "Watch this folder. If you see a new log line, send it to Elasticsearch immediately." 

The Registry: Filebeat keeps a small "Registry File" (a digital bookmark). It remembers exactly which line of which file it last read. 

 

Pros and Cons 

Pros (The Benefits): 

Ultra-Low Overhead: Writing to a local disk is significantly faster than making a network call. Our application won't slow down, even if the network is busy. 

Built-in Safety: If the network goes out, the data is already safely written to the disk. It’s not sitting in the "volatile" memory of the app. 

Easy Debugging: If we suspect data isn't moving, we can simply open the log file on the server and see exactly what the app tried to send. 

Cons (The Challenges): 

Disk Space Management: We must manage the log files. If we don't "rotate" (delete old files), we could fill up the server's hard drive. 

Server Access: Filebeat needs to be installed on the same server/container as the Spring Boot app. 

 

Java Implementation & Setup 

1. Spring Boot Setup (logback-spring.xml) 

We configure our app to write to a file in JSON format. 

code Xml 

downloadcontent_copy 

expand_less 

<appender name="SEARCH_SYNC_FILE" class="ch.qos.logback.core.rolling.RollingFileAppender"> 
   <file>/logs/search-data.json</file> 
   <encoder class="net.logstash.logback.encoder.LogstashEncoder" /> 
   <rollingPolicy class="ch.qos.logback.core.rolling.SizeAndTimeBasedRollingPolicy"> 
       <fileNamePattern>/logs/search-data-%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.%i.json</fileNamePattern> 
       <maxFileSize>100MB</maxFileSize> 
       <maxHistory>7</maxHistory> <!-- Keep 7 days of logs as backup --> 
   </rollingPolicy> 
</appender> 

2. Filebeat Setup (filebeat.yml) 

We tell Filebeat where to look and where to send. 

code Yaml 

