filebeat.inputs: 
- type: log 
 paths: 
   - /logs/search-data.json 
 json.keys_under_root: true 
 
output.elasticsearch: 
 hosts: ["https://our-es-cluster:9200"] 
 api_key: "our-api-key" 

 

Failure Scenarios & Our Solutions 

Potential Failure 

What Happens? 

Our Solution 

Elasticsearch is Offline 

Filebeat cannot deliver the data. 

The Registry Bookmark: Filebeat stops reading the file. It "remembers" the last line it successfully sent. Once ES is back, it resumes from that exact line. 

Spring Boot Crashes 

The app stops writing logs. 

Persistence: Any data written before the crash is already safe on the disk. Filebeat will continue to ship the remaining logs even if the app is down. 

Filebeat Crashes 

The "Courier" stops moving. 

Automatic Resume: When Filebeat restarts, it checks its "Registry File," realizes it is behind, and "tails" the log file at high speed to catch up. 

Disk is Full 

The app cannot write new logs. 

Rotation Policy: We will set a "Rolling Policy" to automatically delete logs older than 7 days or once they exceed a certain size (e.g., 10GB). 

Server Reboots 

Both the app and Filebeat stop. 

Dual Recovery: Upon reboot, Spring Boot starts writing new logs, and Filebeat uses its registry to finish shipping the old logs before starting on the new ones. 

 

Summary of what we are going to use 

Logback + Logstash Encoder: To turn Java objects into JSON log lines. 

Linux Disk Storage: To act as our temporary "waiting room." 

Filebeat Agent: The lightweight delivery service. 

Log Rotation: To ensure we don't run out of disk space. 

 

 

This section details Option 4, which we call the "Processing Station" strategy. In this model, our application sends data directly over the network to a central "middleman" (Logstash), which cleans, transforms, and delivers the data to Elasticsearch. 

 

Option 4: The "Middleman" (The Processing Station Strategy) 

How it Works (The Concept) 

Instead of writing to a file or a message broker, our Spring Boot app opens a direct "phone line" (a TCP or HTTP connection) to Logstash. 

As our app processes database records, it "streams" them immediately to Logstash. Logstash acts like a specialized factory—it receives the raw data, formats it, adds extra information (like timestamps or geography), and then pushes it into Elasticsearch. 

 

Our Implementation Steps 

The Logstash Setup: We set up one or more Logstash instances. We configure them to "listen" for incoming data on a specific network port (e.g., port 5044). 

The Load Balancer: To ensure we are always online, we place a Load Balancer (like NGINX or F5) in front of our Logstash instances. If one Logstash station goes down, the "phone call" from our app is automatically routed to a healthy one. 

The App Configuration: We add the logstash-logback-encoder to our Spring Boot app. We tell the app to send its search data to the Load Balancer's IP address. 

The Transformation: We write "Filters" in Logstash to clean the data (e.g., "Remove sensitive user info" or "Fix date formats") before it hits the search engine. 

 

Pros and Cons 

Pros (The Benefits): 

Centralized Logic: We can change how our data is formatted in Logstash without ever restarting or re-coding our main Spring Boot application. 

Lean Application: Our app doesn't need to know anything about Elasticsearch. It just sends data to one place (Logstash) and forgets about it. 

Easy Transformation: Logstash is incredibly powerful at "mutating" data—it can combine fields, calculate values, and enrich data very easily. 

Cons (The Challenges): 

Network Dependency: Since data travels over the network, if our internal network is slow or unstable, data delivery can be delayed. 

Potential Data Loss: If Logstash and the Load Balancer are both down at the same time, the app might have nowhere to send the data (unless we use a local buffer). 

 

Failure Scenarios & Our Solutions 

Potential Failure 

What Happens? 

Our Solution 

Logstash is Offline 

The app tries to "call" Logstash but gets no answer. 

Persistent Queues (PQ): We will enable Logstash's "Persistent Queue" feature. This means once Logstash receives data, it writes it to its own disk immediately so it can't be lost even if the power goes out. 

Network Hiccup 

The connection between the app and Logstash is temporarily cut. 

Async Buffer: We will configure the Spring Boot app to use an "Asynchronous Appender." It will hold a small amount of data in its memory and keep trying to reconnect until the "phone line" is open again. 

Logstash is "Too Busy" 

Our app is sending data faster than Logstash can process it. 

Backpressure: Logstash will signal the app to "slow down." Because we use TCP, the app will naturally wait for Logstash to become available before sending more. 

Elasticsearch is Offline 

Logstash has the data but cannot deliver it to the search engine. 

Output Retries: Logstash will automatically keep the data in its "Persistent Queue" and keep retrying the delivery to Elasticsearch until it succeeds. 

One Logstash Instance Crashes 

50% of our processing power is gone. 

High Availability (HA): Our Load Balancer will detect the crash in milliseconds and automatically send all data to the second Logstash instance. 

 

 

 

Java Implementation & Setup 

1. Spring Boot Setup (logback-spring.xml) 

We tell the app to stream data to the Logstash Load Balancer. 

code Xml 

